From 50252d044fd828264071dec5ca0224d382780b17 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Hans Richardson <harichardson68@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 26 Jun 2026 21:18:40 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/4] Flip location-field US/non-US check from denylist to
 allowlist
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Per Hans's explicit request after the remote4africa.com leak. The old
approach rejected a location only if it matched a known non-US place —
structurally leaky (it took an actual leak to notice Africa was missing
entirely from NON_US_LOCATIONS; the same gap exists for any place nobody
has spotted yet).

New behavior for the structured location field specifically:
  - Empty location: unchanged, stays ambiguous, falls through to the
    title/description checks below (many of Hans's sources just don't
    populate this for genuinely US-eligible postings).
  - Non-empty location: now rejected UNLESS it matches a recognized US
    signal (explicit phrase, US state, major US city, KC-metro term, or
    a standalone 'us' token) or a deferred Canada term. No longer
    possible for an unrecognized country/city to slip through silently.
  - 'Remote (Worldwide)'-style phrasing explicitly overrides the bare
    'remote' allow signal and still rejects.

Title/description text is NOT flipped to an allowlist — that's freeform
prose where requiring positive proof of US-ness would be too brittle.
The existing strong_indicators denylist there is unchanged and still
acts as a backstop.

Hoisted the state/city list (US_STATES_AND_MAJOR_CITIES) to module level
so it's shared between the new allowlist check and the existing
downstream state-restriction logic, instead of two separately-maintained
copies. Preserved the Missouri-exclusion behavior of that downstream
check exactly (filters Missouri back out of the shared list there).

Verified against 16 manual test cases (legit US locations, blank
location, KC-metro, several African/European/Asian countries, Canada
deferral, worldwide override) — all pass.

KNOWN PRE-EXISTING ISSUE FOUND WHILE TESTING (not introduced by this
commit, not fixed here): the downstream state-restriction check's
abbreviation list uses space-padded 2-letter codes (e.g. ' in ' for
Indiana, ' or ' for Oregon) as a crude word-boundary hack. These collide
with common English words ('in', 'or', 'me', 'hi', 'ok', 'la', 'pa',
etc.), so any 'must be located in...' phrasing combined with one of
those short words can cause a false 'other state mentioned' rejection.
Confirmed via test: a literal 'must be located in Missouri' posting gets
incorrectly rejected because the surrounding word 'in' false-matches the
Indiana abbreviation. Flagging for a separate fix — needs real
word-boundary regex (\bin\b style) across the whole abbreviation set,
which is its own focused change.
---
